WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.300 --> 00:00:07.430
JESS: So welcome to our panel
discussion on why food matters.

00:00:07.430 --> 00:00:09.480
So today we have
with us Sam, who

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:11.690
is the second-generation
owner of Bi-Rite

00:00:11.690 --> 00:00:15.670
Market and the founder of the
Bi-Rite family of businesses,

00:00:15.670 --> 00:00:19.410
which includes the two San
Francisco markets, Bi-Rite

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:23.250
Creamery, Bi-Rite Catering,
and Bi-Rite Farms.

00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:27.810
Sam also co-founded and is
on the board of 18 Reasons.

00:00:27.810 --> 00:00:30.410
And then we have Sarah,
who is the Executive

00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:32.720
Director of 18 Reasons.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:35.360
She's worked on food-related
projects in the Bay Area

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:37.110
since 2008.

00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:39.740
She launched the Bay
Area's first Market Match,

00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:42.880
which gives farmers' market
customers who use food stamps

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:45.100
extra funds to
spend at the market,

00:00:45.100 --> 00:00:47.060
and a Veggie RX
program that helps

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:49.280
diabetes patients
increase their produce

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:52.480
consumption while measuring
positive health outcomes.

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:55.650
In 2011, she founded the
nonprofit Three Squares, which

00:00:55.650 --> 00:00:59.070
merged with 18 Reasons in 2013.

00:00:59.070 --> 00:01:01.840
And I'll let them introduce
themselves and tell you

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:05.330
a little bit more about their
backgrounds in a second.

00:01:05.330 --> 00:01:06.810
But first I would
just want to say,

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:08.660
please stick around
after the panel

00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:10.420
to continue the conversation.

00:01:10.420 --> 00:01:13.720
And there will be
ice cream, so I'm

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:16.060
sure that had nothing to
do with why so many of you

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:17.830
are here today.

00:01:17.830 --> 00:01:22.522
But with that, let's
welcome our panel to Google.

00:01:22.522 --> 00:01:26.320
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:29.140
So I'd love to start with
your personal stories.

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:31.020
I don't know if one of
you wants to go first.

00:01:31.020 --> 00:01:32.270
SARAH NELSON: I'm going first.

00:01:32.270 --> 00:01:33.810
SAM MOGANNAM: OK.

00:01:33.810 --> 00:01:35.440
SARAH NELSON: So hi, I'm Sarah.

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:38.970
And I've been working in
nonprofits for a long time.

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:41.100
I originally started
out working in the arts,

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:43.350
and when I moved to San
Francisco eight years ago,

00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:45.080
I found a job working in food.

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:48.000
And it had never really
occurred to me to work in food.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.140
Food was just something
that I loved and did

00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:52.860
and ate every day three times.

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:55.880
But it turns out there's a
whole wonderful world of people

00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:57.680
working in food and
a lot of great things

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:58.840
to do in the field.

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:01.040
So I started working
for farmers' markets,

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:04.880
as Jess said, and I think people
think that farmers' markets are

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:07.190
just a bunch of
farmers who all agreed

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:09.910
to show up at a certain
place on a certain time.

00:02:09.910 --> 00:02:12.810
And that's kind of the illusion
that we want you to have

00:02:12.810 --> 00:02:15.390
but, in fact, farmers' markets
are organized by nonprofits.

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:17.380
The one I worked for
runs 60 farmers' markets

00:02:17.380 --> 00:02:18.730
all over the Bay Area.

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:22.160
So they are organized
and marketed

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:24.870
and permits are managed
and so forth by nonprofits.

00:02:24.870 --> 00:02:27.980
So I was running nutrition
education programs,

00:02:27.980 --> 00:02:30.580
writing grants, which was how
I started out in nonprofits,

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:31.724
was raising money.

00:02:31.724 --> 00:02:33.140
And then left the
farmers' markets

00:02:33.140 --> 00:02:35.940
to start my own nonprofit
based around cooking.

00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:37.780
We were doing cooking
demos in markets,

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:42.050
and I felt that hands-on cooking
experience is so much more

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:45.820
valuable than watching people
cook, whether it's live

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:46.382
or on TV.

00:02:46.382 --> 00:02:47.840
We were talking
about this at lunch

00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:49.620
that people spend
seven hours a week

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:52.390
watching cooking shows on TV
and 30 minutes a week actually

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:53.190
cooking.

00:02:53.190 --> 00:02:55.920
So clearly watching
people cook is not really

00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:57.380
getting them to cook.

00:02:57.380 --> 00:03:00.760
So I started a nonprofit to
teach free cooking classes

00:03:00.760 --> 00:03:03.390
to low-income adults and
kids all over the Bay Area

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:05.737
and, through that, met Sam.

00:03:05.737 --> 00:03:08.070
We asked him to come and speak
at one of our fundraisers

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:09.950
and got involved that way.

00:03:09.950 --> 00:03:13.110
We started a film festival
together as a fundraiser.

00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:16.375
And when the time
was right, 18 Reasons

00:03:16.375 --> 00:03:18.500
was kind of looking to go
in the direction of doing

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:20.050
more free programming.

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:21.740
We were looking to
raise more money

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:24.240
and thought that paid classes
might be a way to raise money,

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.290
and it all kind of
worked out perfectly

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:29.620
that we merged the organizations
together into 18 Reasons

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:32.580
as it is today, which is
a nonprofit offering both

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:35.380
paid classes and events in
our classroom on 18th Street

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:37.640
in the mission as well as
our free Cooking Matters

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:38.849
program out in the community.

00:03:38.849 --> 00:03:40.473
SAM MOGANNAM: And
I'm just going to say

00:03:40.473 --> 00:03:42.580
it's a pretty cool, unique
model, because we've

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:46.270
got a combination of earned
income because of the paid

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:48.880
classes and contributed
income that we get

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:52.891
through either donations
or through grant writing

00:03:52.891 --> 00:03:54.390
and I think a really
important model

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:59.720
for the future sustainability
of nonprofits going forward.

00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:04.320
There's got to be a
combination of both, I think.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:06.730
So I'm Sam Mogannam.

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:08.800
As Jess said, I'm the
second-generation owner

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:11.190
of Bi-Rite.

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:19.320
I grew up in it and wanted
nothing but to get out of it

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:20.029
my whole youth.

00:04:20.029 --> 00:04:22.380
I literally spent
the years from 6

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:26.990
until I was 17 working
at my father's store.

00:04:26.990 --> 00:04:30.000
My father and uncle bought
the business in 1964,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.450
so well over 50 years ago.

00:04:32.450 --> 00:04:34.480
And the market itself
has been on 18th Street

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:37.990
since 1940, so
over 75 years now.

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:41.500
And many of you who have been
in San Francisco long enough

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:45.500
have seen how rapidly the
city, especially its heritage

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:47.070
businesses, have changed.

00:04:47.070 --> 00:04:50.020
And it's something that
I'm very proud of, the fact

00:04:50.020 --> 00:04:55.740
that the single-story building
with the original facade

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:58.660
has lasted as long as it has.

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:01.050
So after school, I would go
and I would sweep the floors,

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:02.280
and then I learned how
to stock the shelves

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:03.488
in then ring on the register.

00:05:03.488 --> 00:05:05.920
Eventually, I was buying
wine when I was 15.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:07.770
I had no idea what
it tasted like,

00:05:07.770 --> 00:05:11.510
but I was making these beautiful
displays, and at one point

00:05:11.510 --> 00:05:14.070
Bi-Rite was selling
more Beringer White

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:17.410
Zinfandel than any other
grocery store in San Francisco.

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:21.150
And all the Gallo sales reps
came down and descended on it,

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:23.970
like they had the Regional
Sales Director come in.

00:05:23.970 --> 00:05:25.710
It's like, who is
the wine buyer here?

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:28.220
And my dad introduced
me to them.

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:30.760
And they're like going, what?

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:33.702
And they were offering
me jobs, saying, well,

00:05:33.702 --> 00:05:35.160
when you graduate
from high school,

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:37.830
we want to put you into our
management development program.

00:05:37.830 --> 00:05:41.147
I was like, I don't know
if I want to do that.

00:05:41.147 --> 00:05:42.730
But when I graduated
from high school,

00:05:42.730 --> 00:05:45.690
I thought I was going
to become a hotel guy,

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:50.510
and my intent was to eventually
get to Cornell and started off

00:05:50.510 --> 00:05:54.200
here at City College of San
Francisco and tried to get

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:56.349
a job in a hotel and couldn't.

00:05:56.349 --> 00:05:57.890
Nobody would give
me a job, because I

00:05:57.890 --> 00:05:59.460
didn't have any experience.

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:01.520
I think all of us
have been there.

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:04.750
And it forced me to
kind of seek work

00:06:04.750 --> 00:06:06.900
in hospitality
outside of hotels.

00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:10.250
And so I started
applying in restaurants

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:12.840
and got a lot of
the same answer.

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:14.530
No experience, no job.

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:16.840
Finally I had a young chef
who took a chance on me

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:18.140
and hired me to be a prep cook.

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:22.610
And I fell in love and within
three months of cooking

00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:28.610
at this diner, I was the head
cook and in an open kitchen,

00:06:28.610 --> 00:06:30.760
getting a chance
to watch people eat

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:33.086
the food that I was cooking.

00:06:33.086 --> 00:06:35.460
And then they would come up
and say thank you and tell me

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:36.880
how great it was.

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:38.652
And I immediately
realized that this

00:06:38.652 --> 00:06:40.610
is what I wanted to do
for the rest of my life.

00:06:40.610 --> 00:06:44.040
And I was 18, and I
feel super lucky that I

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:46.560
discovered what I wanted to
do for the rest of my life

00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:48.850
so early on.

00:06:48.850 --> 00:06:52.150
And spent the next
dozen or so years

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:55.520
cooking in various
restaurants, seven of which-- I

00:06:55.520 --> 00:06:57.820
had my own restaurant down
in the Financial District

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:00.150
not too far from here,
over on Bush and Kearney,

00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:04.130
close to the Chinatown gates,
and I opened that business

00:07:04.130 --> 00:07:06.300
when I was 23.

00:07:06.300 --> 00:07:10.680
And then a few years
later opened up,

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:14.820
in 1994, San Francisco's first
organic coffee and juice bar.

00:07:14.820 --> 00:07:18.970
It was so far ahead of its
time that it didn't succeed.

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:24.710
We literally struggled.

00:07:24.710 --> 00:07:27.640
Back then, a 50-pound
box of carrots

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:29.920
was anywhere between
$70 and $90 a box,

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:33.020
and now it's about
$25 to $30 a case.

00:07:33.020 --> 00:07:35.090
So you can imagine
the economics.

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:39.070
And back then, people
were not paying $8 to $10

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:40.400
for a fresh-pressed juice.

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.410
They were only willing
to pay about $3.

00:07:42.410 --> 00:07:44.760
And so you can do
the math and begin

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:47.320
to understand the struggles.

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:49.390
And then Jamba Juice
opened up right

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:51.670
across the street from us.

00:07:51.670 --> 00:07:54.930
And that pretty much
was the kiss of death.

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:58.660
My brother and I, with our
heads between our legs,

00:07:58.660 --> 00:08:00.730
sold it and walked away from it.

00:08:00.730 --> 00:08:03.620
It was sad, but it was
an important failure

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:09.820
because it taught me that we
had to learn how to meet people

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:13.641
on their own terms, meet them
in some sort of middle ground

00:08:13.641 --> 00:08:16.140
for them to feel comfortable
with what we were offering them

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:20.550
and not offer something
that was so polarizing,

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:23.440
that was such a niche market.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:27.740
And so when we opened
Bi-Rite in 1998,

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:32.460
we took that philosophy,
that mentality, and also just

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:37.280
the mentality and philosophy
of a cook, someone

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:39.870
who feeds people, and applied
it to a grocery store.

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:44.070
And when we first opened, not
all our produce was organic.

00:08:44.070 --> 00:08:47.980
I'd say about half-- 40%
might have been organic.

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:51.400
Of that, maybe a quarter
of it was farm direct.

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:55.150
We had conventional bananas
and other conventional fruit

00:08:55.150 --> 00:09:01.707
and vegetables, because price
sensitivity was a major issue.

00:09:01.707 --> 00:09:03.290
And we wanted to
make sure that people

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:06.700
felt like they could access
the food that we were selling.

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:12.050
And slowly, through education--
I consider myself a feeder,

00:09:12.050 --> 00:09:15.170
but I also consider myself a
teacher-- through this process,

00:09:15.170 --> 00:09:17.220
we evolved.

00:09:17.220 --> 00:09:19.691
And as a business, we
evolved and as a neighborhood

00:09:19.691 --> 00:09:20.940
and as a community we evolved.

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:23.750
And we've grown together.

00:09:23.750 --> 00:09:26.980
And we started with
a staff of six,

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:30.550
and now we've got about
315 people working for us

00:09:30.550 --> 00:09:35.400
in the company and have a
tremendous reach and influence

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:39.320
around the country
with how we operate

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:42.450
and how we view business.

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:43.290
Yeah.

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:46.110
It's been a super cool fun ride.

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:48.610
JESS: I just want to ask the
audience a few questions first.

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:51.440
How many of you
identify as home cooks?

00:09:53.990 --> 00:09:54.490
Cool.

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:57.566
And then how many of you
are familiar with Bi-Rite.

00:09:57.566 --> 00:09:58.950
SAM MOGANNAM: Oh, cool.

00:09:58.950 --> 00:09:59.620
JESS: Awesome.

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:01.990
SAM MOGANNAM: Fantastic.

00:10:01.990 --> 00:10:04.800
JESS: And how many of you
have taken a cooking class?

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:07.790
Maybe not necessarily at 18
Reasons but anywhere else,

00:10:07.790 --> 00:10:10.880
and that includes knife
skills or anything like that.

00:10:10.880 --> 00:10:11.500
OK.

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:14.107
So this is a good room.

00:10:14.107 --> 00:10:15.440
SAM MOGANNAM: The choir is here.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:17.731
JESS: How many of you brought
your lunch to work today?

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:21.990
Uh-huh.

00:10:21.990 --> 00:10:24.655
Uh-huh.

00:10:24.655 --> 00:10:26.030
So I want to pick
up on something

00:10:26.030 --> 00:10:29.120
that you said, and this will
be a question for both of you.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:31.270
You said the
philosophy of a cook

00:10:31.270 --> 00:10:34.030
is what you apply to
Bi-Rite, and so I wanted

00:10:34.030 --> 00:10:37.230
to talk a little bit about
of your ultimate mission

00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:39.140
behind Bi-Rite and
what that means,

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:40.220
the philosophy of a cook.

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:43.260
And then, similarly, how that
sort of extends to the work

00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:45.770
that you do at 18
Reasons and what's

00:10:45.770 --> 00:10:47.970
really driving that stuff.

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:50.015
SAM MOGANNAM: They
dovetail pretty seamlessly.

00:10:53.096 --> 00:10:53.690
I don't know.

00:10:53.690 --> 00:10:57.870
I was probably in my early 20s
when I came to the realization

00:10:57.870 --> 00:11:02.450
that as a cook I had this
extraordinary responsibility

00:11:02.450 --> 00:11:04.200
to the person that
I was feeding.

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:09.970
I got to select the ingredients,
prep them, wash them,

00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:14.230
cut them, and then
cook them and season

00:11:14.230 --> 00:11:16.630
them and taste them
through this process

00:11:16.630 --> 00:11:20.840
and watch them evolve and
then put them on a plate

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:23.861
and try to make it as pretty and
beautiful as I possibly could

00:11:23.861 --> 00:11:25.360
and then hand that
plate to somebody

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:26.590
and then watch them
to actually take it

00:11:26.590 --> 00:11:27.923
and put it in their body, right?

00:11:27.923 --> 00:11:29.930
Put it in their
mouth, and then they

00:11:29.930 --> 00:11:34.560
they'd experience the beautiful
acids and salts and sugars

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:36.590
and bitters and whatever
other flavors were

00:11:36.590 --> 00:11:40.880
going on in this dish,
which was transformative.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:43.760
All of us have had these
really magical experiences

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:47.510
when we eat something that's
super profound and delicious.

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:49.210
It puts us in a
different place, right?

00:11:49.210 --> 00:11:51.550
It makes us either
feel really great

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:54.330
or makes us feel
shitty, depending

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:55.710
on who it is that's feeding us.

00:11:55.710 --> 00:11:58.980
And I definitely wanted
to make people feel great.

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:01.190
I didn't want to
make them feel sick.

00:12:01.190 --> 00:12:08.060
And so I took that same
sense of mission, that belief

00:12:08.060 --> 00:12:10.110
that it all starts
with great ingredients,

00:12:10.110 --> 00:12:12.990
knowing where those ingredients
come from, making sure

00:12:12.990 --> 00:12:17.760
that they're grown while knowing
where they're being grown,

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:21.060
who grew them, and kind
of like applied that

00:12:21.060 --> 00:12:24.650
to almost everything that we
sell in the grocery store.

00:12:24.650 --> 00:12:28.420
And as a cook, I was
yearning for a place

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:32.280
to go shop in San Francisco that
had all the ingredients that I

00:12:32.280 --> 00:12:34.680
was accustomed to
using as a chef.

00:12:34.680 --> 00:12:38.970
And back in '98, that
really didn't exist.

00:12:38.970 --> 00:12:40.670
There weren't very
many stores where

00:12:40.670 --> 00:12:44.395
you can go and have a selection
of a dozen vinegars, where

00:12:44.395 --> 00:12:47.870
you'd be able to go and get Star
Red Wine Vinegar, Star White

00:12:47.870 --> 00:12:50.400
Wine Vinegar, and
Monari Balsamic Vinegar.

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:52.890
And those were
the three vinegars

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:54.660
that every supermarket had.

00:12:54.660 --> 00:12:57.900
But to find vinegar from
the Southwest of France,

00:12:57.900 --> 00:13:01.040
from the Banyul grape, or
to find sherry wine vinegar

00:13:01.040 --> 00:13:08.940
or to find beautiful single
varietal grape-based vinegars

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:10.150
just didn't happen.

00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:12.720
And these are magical
ingredients that

00:13:12.720 --> 00:13:14.000
really can transform a dish.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.050
And so we wanted to
have the ingredients,

00:13:18.050 --> 00:13:22.620
but we also wanted to have
the acumen, because it's

00:13:22.620 --> 00:13:24.560
one thing to sell
those ingredients,

00:13:24.560 --> 00:13:28.160
but you have to be able to
teach people how to use them.

00:13:28.160 --> 00:13:31.670
And so we surrounded
ourselves with a staff

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:35.930
of folks that love to cook
and worked in restaurants.

00:13:35.930 --> 00:13:38.620
And if they weren't
cooks, they were

00:13:38.620 --> 00:13:42.130
servers who had spent time
working with chefs that

00:13:42.130 --> 00:13:43.624
taught them a lot about food.

00:13:43.624 --> 00:13:45.040
And so we were
teaching people how

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:46.706
to use the ingredients
at the same time.

00:13:46.706 --> 00:13:50.590
We're empowering people and
helping them elevate the food

00:13:50.590 --> 00:13:52.840
that they were serving,
feeding themselves and feeding

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:53.465
their families.

00:13:56.150 --> 00:14:03.170
And to me, cooking is one of
those foundational basic skills

00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:07.630
that each of us needs to
embrace and to celebrate,

00:14:07.630 --> 00:14:11.020
because it not only
ensures that you're

00:14:11.020 --> 00:14:13.110
able to feed
yourself really well,

00:14:13.110 --> 00:14:15.860
but it creates this
opportunity to share.

00:14:15.860 --> 00:14:19.440
And it's so wonderful to
be able to feed somebody

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:22.110
and then to get that
immediate reward from it.

00:14:22.110 --> 00:14:25.060
But it's also really wonderful
to sit around the table

00:14:25.060 --> 00:14:29.290
and to break bread and to talk.

00:14:29.290 --> 00:14:32.160
And that's how
relationships get built.

00:14:32.160 --> 00:14:35.179
And our mission at Bi-Rite
is creating community

00:14:35.179 --> 00:14:35.720
through food.

00:14:35.720 --> 00:14:38.650
And that's about
building relationships,

00:14:38.650 --> 00:14:40.920
deep meaningful relationships,
and I feel really

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:44.210
strongly that if we're
able to, as a society,

00:14:44.210 --> 00:14:47.630
make stronger bonds, be
more intimately connected,

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:53.800
then we will achieve change
and become a strong stronger

00:14:53.800 --> 00:14:57.140
community together and really
be supportive and helpful

00:14:57.140 --> 00:14:59.080
to each other.

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:01.890
And 18 Reasons just
steps right in there

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:05.900
and actually takes
what we're able to do

00:15:05.900 --> 00:15:09.170
on a very transactional
basis, I would say,

00:15:09.170 --> 00:15:11.590
because our interactions
in the market

00:15:11.590 --> 00:15:15.839
can be anywhere between 2
and 10 minutes, depending.

00:15:15.839 --> 00:15:17.880
And with the classes that
we offer at 18 Reasons,

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:20.010
and Sarah will talk
more about their impact,

00:15:20.010 --> 00:15:25.120
that we're able to take
control of or ownership

00:15:25.120 --> 00:15:27.180
of that experience
for a period of two

00:15:27.180 --> 00:15:32.040
to three hours, which really
lets us go much deeper.

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:32.950
SARAH NELSON: Yeah.

00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:36.070
We teach Basic Knife
Skills about twice a month,

00:15:36.070 --> 00:15:37.980
and it's the fastest
class to sell out.

00:15:37.980 --> 00:15:39.530
It's the most in-demand class.

00:15:39.530 --> 00:15:41.680
And our chef said
to me recently,

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:43.910
I can't believe there's
anyone in San Francisco who

00:15:43.910 --> 00:15:47.240
hasn't taken our Basic Knife
Skills class at this point.

00:15:47.240 --> 00:15:49.510
And people come up to her
at the farmers' market

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:53.450
and tell her things they
remember from the Basic Knife

00:15:53.450 --> 00:15:54.110
Skills class.

00:15:54.110 --> 00:15:58.320
And it always amazes me too
that this very simple skill is

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:00.230
lacking in people's lives.

00:16:00.230 --> 00:16:06.190
And to me, cooking is one
tool of self-empowerment

00:16:06.190 --> 00:16:11.070
and taking control over your own
and doing things for yourself.

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:14.430
And knowing how to use a
knife, it's not that hard.

00:16:14.430 --> 00:16:18.690
We do a lot of things that are
harder, like play "Pokemon Go."

00:16:18.690 --> 00:16:20.820
I don't have a clue
how to do that.

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:24.100
But using a knife, people come
into our knife skills class,

00:16:24.100 --> 00:16:25.760
and they're so
scared, and they're

00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:28.304
so nervous and just
watching them pick up

00:16:28.304 --> 00:16:30.220
the knife for the first
time, and they're just

00:16:30.220 --> 00:16:31.629
so worried about it.

00:16:31.629 --> 00:16:33.920
And by the end of the class,
like they're just relaxed,

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:35.800
they're so happy they've
mastered the skill.

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:38.050
And that's all you really
need to go and cook anything

00:16:38.050 --> 00:16:39.174
that you want for yourself.

00:16:39.174 --> 00:16:42.199
And so even in our paid classes
or in our free classes where

00:16:42.199 --> 00:16:43.740
we get a lot of
folks who don't cook,

00:16:43.740 --> 00:16:45.500
they've never cooked
before, they have never

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:47.083
used some of the
vegetables that we're

00:16:47.083 --> 00:16:49.710
using, they're intimidated
by trying new things,

00:16:49.710 --> 00:16:52.470
trying new skills, by the end
of that class, they're so happy.

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:54.960
They've mastered this
wonderful new skill.

00:16:54.960 --> 00:16:57.770
And I think cooking, along with
a lot of other home-ec skills,

00:16:57.770 --> 00:16:59.650
have been completely lost.

00:16:59.650 --> 00:17:04.690
How many people are still sewing
their own buttons on and fixing

00:17:04.690 --> 00:17:07.550
their cars and building
things in their woodshops

00:17:07.550 --> 00:17:08.450
in their garage?

00:17:08.450 --> 00:17:11.619
And things that used to be
taught in school that are not

00:17:11.619 --> 00:17:16.165
taught in school anymore because
the corporations that control

00:17:16.165 --> 00:17:18.789
us don't want us to know how to
do things for ourselves, right?

00:17:18.789 --> 00:17:20.680
No, seriously.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:23.930
Who used their body
to get to work today?

00:17:23.930 --> 00:17:26.290
Who walked or rode a bike?

00:17:26.290 --> 00:17:27.130
Good job.

00:17:27.130 --> 00:17:28.760
You did something for yourself.

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:31.940
You took that power,
and you did it yourself.

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:33.820
Who cleans their own house?

00:17:33.820 --> 00:17:34.450
Awesome.

00:17:34.450 --> 00:17:35.670
You guys are awesome.

00:17:35.670 --> 00:17:37.219
You take care of your own shit.

00:17:37.219 --> 00:17:37.760
That's great.

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:39.180
I love it.

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:41.000
We're just encouraged
all the time

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.290
by corporations
trying to make money

00:17:43.290 --> 00:17:45.650
that we shouldn't do any of
these things for ourselves.

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:48.175
We should take an Uber,
like why would you walk?

00:17:48.175 --> 00:17:49.383
Why would you ride your bike?

00:17:49.383 --> 00:17:50.470
It's so easy.

00:17:50.470 --> 00:17:53.041
You shouldn't clean your own
clothes or do your own laundry

00:17:53.041 --> 00:17:54.040
or clean your own house.

00:17:54.040 --> 00:17:55.240
You shouldn't cook
your own food.

00:17:55.240 --> 00:17:56.530
Why would you want to
cook your own food?

00:17:56.530 --> 00:17:58.380
Like there's all this
just great food out there.

00:17:58.380 --> 00:17:59.463
Just eat what we give you.

00:17:59.463 --> 00:18:03.262
And a lot of it, yes, things
have made our lives easier.

00:18:03.262 --> 00:18:04.720
Have you guys read
Michael Pollan's

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:06.320
"Cooked," his last book?

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:09.080
He points out that when all
these labor-saving devices were

00:18:09.080 --> 00:18:10.524
coming around in
the '50s, cooking

00:18:10.524 --> 00:18:12.690
was the one chore that
housewives said they actually

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:15.040
enjoyed, and they didn't want
it to be taken away from them.

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:16.456
And the reason
that you still have

00:18:16.456 --> 00:18:19.020
to add an egg to a cake mix
is because that gives you

00:18:19.020 --> 00:18:20.417
the illusion that
you're cooking.

00:18:20.417 --> 00:18:22.750
They could have powdered the
egg and thrown it in there,

00:18:22.750 --> 00:18:24.083
but people wouldn't go for that.

00:18:24.083 --> 00:18:26.936
People still want
to cook in some way.

00:18:26.936 --> 00:18:28.060
And so you add that egg in.

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:30.442
You feel like you're actually
making that cake yourself.

00:18:30.442 --> 00:18:31.900
And so I feel like
people do really

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:34.870
want to use their
brains and their bodies

00:18:34.870 --> 00:18:36.172
to take care of themselves.

00:18:36.172 --> 00:18:37.630
But it's getting
harder and harder.

00:18:37.630 --> 00:18:39.350
We're encouraged not to do it.

00:18:39.350 --> 00:18:41.590
And cooking for
yourself really brings

00:18:41.590 --> 00:18:43.100
that sense of empowerment.

00:18:43.100 --> 00:18:45.140
And then also, as
Sam was touching on,

00:18:45.140 --> 00:18:47.680
connection to the people
who made that food

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:50.677
and to your family as well.

00:18:50.677 --> 00:18:52.260
I'm serious about
bringing your lunch.

00:18:52.260 --> 00:18:54.220
I bring my own lunch
to work every day,

00:18:54.220 --> 00:18:56.550
and it's usually leftovers
of what me and my boyfriend

00:18:56.550 --> 00:18:57.630
made last night.

00:18:57.630 --> 00:18:59.370
And for me, it's like
a point in the day

00:18:59.370 --> 00:19:02.110
when I think about my
boyfriend and the dinner

00:19:02.110 --> 00:19:04.040
we had last night and
my connection with him,

00:19:04.040 --> 00:19:05.690
and sometimes we text
each other, like,

00:19:05.690 --> 00:19:08.106
thanks for the great lunch,
whichever one of us cooked it.

00:19:08.106 --> 00:19:09.940
And it gives me that connection.

00:19:09.940 --> 00:19:11.440
I know exactly what
that food means,

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:13.110
and it's our food,
even if it's not

00:19:13.110 --> 00:19:16.970
as good as the amazing lunch
I just had in your cafe.

00:19:16.970 --> 00:19:19.686
We made risotto last night
and had some risotto,

00:19:19.686 --> 00:19:21.310
and I had a raw
pepper, so I cut it up,

00:19:21.310 --> 00:19:24.210
and I had this lunch that was
like risotto and a raw pepper.

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:25.279
Like who cares?

00:19:25.279 --> 00:19:27.070
But it was a risotto
that we made together,

00:19:27.070 --> 00:19:29.080
and peppers are good
for you, so whatever.

00:19:29.080 --> 00:19:31.934
And it just makes me think
about my family and my home,

00:19:31.934 --> 00:19:34.350
and it makes me happy to do
that and have that connection.

00:19:34.350 --> 00:19:37.700
And the food that's here,
it's amazing and wonderful and

00:19:37.700 --> 00:19:38.740
futuristic.

00:19:38.740 --> 00:19:40.700
My best friend is the
Food Director for Sprig,

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:42.720
and she came to dinner at my
house, and we ordered Sprig.

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:44.690
And it arrived, and this
food was in front of us

00:19:44.690 --> 00:19:45.600
just like the food
you guys have here,

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:47.260
very healthy, local, seasonal.

00:19:47.260 --> 00:19:48.390
I'm like this is weird.

00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:49.230
I'm in the future.

00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:51.990
Food just showed up, and
it's delicious and healthy.

00:19:51.990 --> 00:19:54.070
But who, where, what is this?

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:55.880
Like what connection is there?

00:19:55.880 --> 00:19:56.740
Who grew this food?

00:19:56.740 --> 00:19:57.600
Who made this food?

00:19:57.600 --> 00:19:59.230
I had nothing to
do with this food.

00:19:59.230 --> 00:20:02.200
And having that experience
of cooking yourself,

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:03.742
cooking with your
friends and family,

00:20:03.742 --> 00:20:06.033
even if it's not that great,
just make a grilled cheese

00:20:06.033 --> 00:20:08.280
sandwich, and you can feel
really proud of yourself

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:11.970
for doing that and feel
a moment of humanity

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:16.061
that the man is trying to take
away from us all the time.

00:20:16.061 --> 00:20:16.560
Seriously.

00:20:16.560 --> 00:20:19.044
I kind of an anarchist.

00:20:19.044 --> 00:20:20.037
SAM MOGANNAM: Really?

00:20:20.037 --> 00:20:21.370
SARAH NELSON: Just a little bit.

00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:23.530
Just a little bit.

00:20:23.530 --> 00:20:25.720
I do think it's wonderful
that Google provides you

00:20:25.720 --> 00:20:28.685
such good food, because I
think a lot of young people

00:20:28.685 --> 00:20:30.060
are working in
the tech industry,

00:20:30.060 --> 00:20:32.130
and I've seen it,
people who are my age

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:33.630
and starting to
have kids and not

00:20:33.630 --> 00:20:35.260
eat dinner at work every day.

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:37.670
They're taking that food
they're used to-- you

00:20:37.670 --> 00:20:39.850
guys are used to really
high-quality food-- that's

00:20:39.850 --> 00:20:41.690
what you're going to
cook for your families.

00:20:41.690 --> 00:20:44.260
So when this tech generation
grows up a little bit

00:20:44.260 --> 00:20:47.426
and stops being at work 24
hours a day, and I've seen it,

00:20:47.426 --> 00:20:48.300
like friends of mine.

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:49.800
A friend of mine
who works at Apple,

00:20:49.800 --> 00:20:51.430
