about anything else.

00:23:09.290 --> 00:23:13.840
And so to the extent that you
have either seen people really

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:16.940
have those kind of awakenings
when they're shopping

00:23:16.940 --> 00:23:18.610
or when they're
in the class, I'd

00:23:18.610 --> 00:23:20.910
love to hear your
thoughts on that

00:23:20.910 --> 00:23:23.129
and if that's been
effective for you.

00:23:23.129 --> 00:23:23.920
SAM MOGANNAM: Yeah.

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:28.390
I agree that it is.

00:23:28.390 --> 00:23:31.180
There couldn't be a
more perfect balance

00:23:31.180 --> 00:23:35.050
of science and
technology in that sense

00:23:35.050 --> 00:23:39.340
that you've got to
follow a recipe.

00:23:39.340 --> 00:23:42.840
And there are measurements
and ingredients.

00:23:42.840 --> 00:23:48.090
There's a whole
scientific aspect to it,

00:23:48.090 --> 00:23:51.180
but then there's this
really amazing creative side

00:23:51.180 --> 00:23:53.890
and the spontaneous side.

00:23:53.890 --> 00:23:57.210
And then there's
this whole-- and it's

00:23:57.210 --> 00:23:59.872
not innate for all of us,
but like instinctual side

00:23:59.872 --> 00:24:01.330
that after you've
done it, then you

00:24:01.330 --> 00:24:05.040
can begin to add your
own flair and adapt

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:12.769
and really be super creative
and fun with the ingredients

00:24:12.769 --> 00:24:14.560
that you select and
the adaptation that you

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:15.770
do with particular recipes.

00:24:18.450 --> 00:24:20.610
Any time I have ever
cooked with anybody

00:24:20.610 --> 00:24:23.600
and gone through the process
and handed them the knife

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:25.100
and shown them how
to hold the knife

00:24:25.100 --> 00:24:28.140
and then had them walk through
the sauteing or roasting

00:24:28.140 --> 00:24:32.450
process, they're stimulating
parts of their brain

00:24:32.450 --> 00:24:35.290
that they haven't exercised.

00:24:35.290 --> 00:24:39.210
And those endorphins that
come from that process

00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:43.590
are extremely energizing
and uplifting.

00:24:43.590 --> 00:24:46.620
And, inevitably, I've
never actually seen

00:24:46.620 --> 00:24:49.450
it not bring a smile to
somebody's face and the sense

00:24:49.450 --> 00:24:55.550
of fulfillment that comes from
the process of transforming

00:24:55.550 --> 00:24:58.910
a whole head of cauliflower into
a beautiful roasted cauliflower

00:24:58.910 --> 00:25:00.980
that we ate today for lunch.

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:02.430
And that's part
of what worries me

00:25:02.430 --> 00:25:05.370
about things like Sprig and
these other meal kit companies,

00:25:05.370 --> 00:25:07.990
is we're going to
eventually get to this place

00:25:07.990 --> 00:25:10.440
where people aren't
even going to know

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:14.279
what a whole head of
cauliflower looks like.

00:25:14.279 --> 00:25:16.320
There was this whole thing
that was done on kids,

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:23.400
and they asked them to
draw where beef comes from,

00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:26.250
and they drew pictures of
steak, because they had no idea

00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:28.900
that steak came from cows.

00:25:28.900 --> 00:25:33.530
And I have seen it
in our own store.

00:25:33.530 --> 00:25:36.705
We often will have little
groups of kids come in,

00:25:36.705 --> 00:25:38.350
and one of the first
things that I do

00:25:38.350 --> 00:25:40.540
is take them to the produce
counter and just kind of

00:25:40.540 --> 00:25:43.040
get a sense of whether they
know what their veggies are.

00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:44.540
And I'll point to
particular veggies

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:46.740
and ask them to
just tell me what

00:25:46.740 --> 00:25:49.940
they are, things like
cauliflower and broccoli

00:25:49.940 --> 00:25:52.990
and eggplant, celery.

00:25:52.990 --> 00:25:55.030
They have no idea what it is.

00:25:55.030 --> 00:25:56.530
And then when you
tell them, they're

00:25:56.530 --> 00:25:58.613
like, oh, I didn't know
that that's what that was.

00:25:58.613 --> 00:26:00.060
I had never heard of that.

00:26:00.060 --> 00:26:01.850
These are like 8
to 10-year-olds,

00:26:01.850 --> 00:26:03.360
and it's kind of scary.

00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:07.100
And if we continue to
rely on diced up precut,

00:26:07.100 --> 00:26:12.610
prewashed everything, then
that connection to what I feel

00:26:12.610 --> 00:26:15.300
is like a foundation
to who we are as people

00:26:15.300 --> 00:26:18.980
and what has actually been
the foundation of what created

00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:21.710
society, if it wasn't
for modern agriculture,

00:26:21.710 --> 00:26:24.720
we would still be running
around with spears

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:27.250
chasing after animals.

00:26:27.250 --> 00:26:31.580
That's really what created
the first communities was

00:26:31.580 --> 00:26:33.175
the agricultural
communities that

00:26:33.175 --> 00:26:36.590
were created in Mesopotamia.

00:26:36.590 --> 00:26:39.540
Food's critical for
us, and we need it,

00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:41.740
and we need to be empowered
with that knowledge

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.475
and that information to be
able to do it for ourselves.

00:26:48.090 --> 00:26:50.380
JESS: Amen.

00:26:50.380 --> 00:26:52.170
SARAH NELSON: I
think one thing that

00:26:52.170 --> 00:26:54.880
makes 18 Reasons kind of unique
among other cooking schools

00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:57.310
is that the person teaching
our Indian cooking class

00:26:57.310 --> 00:27:00.460
is from India, and the person
teaching our Italian class

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:01.580
is from Italy.

00:27:01.580 --> 00:27:04.750
And they are mostly not
trained chefs, unfortunately,

00:27:04.750 --> 00:27:06.570
for our beloved
volunteers who have

00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:08.770
to wash dishes behind them.

00:27:08.770 --> 00:27:11.224
Chefs are amazing
humans who really

00:27:11.224 --> 00:27:13.890
know how to get things done in a
clean and wonderfully organized

00:27:13.890 --> 00:27:17.895
way, and home cooks are amazing,
but they're super messy.

00:27:17.895 --> 00:27:20.280
And we have these
really passionate home

00:27:20.280 --> 00:27:24.420
cooks who come to us and
say, look, I'm from wherever.

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:27.390
I'm from Iran, and I really want
to do this traditional-- I want

00:27:27.390 --> 00:27:28.845
to teach a class
on Northern Iran,

00:27:28.845 --> 00:27:30.470
but then I want to
do a different class

00:27:30.470 --> 00:27:31.700
on Western Iran.

00:27:31.700 --> 00:27:32.970
I'm like, great.

00:27:32.970 --> 00:27:35.730
Who knew Northern and Western
Iran are so different?

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:38.890
And those are the kind of
teachers who come to us.

00:27:38.890 --> 00:27:41.450
They mostly find us, and
then we have these classes

00:27:41.450 --> 00:27:45.350
where you really delve into
a culture and the ingredients

00:27:45.350 --> 00:27:49.370
and that kind of 360-degree
experience of a completely

00:27:49.370 --> 00:27:53.140
different place but with that
same love for home cooking.

00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:57.740
And a lot of the recipes in our
classes you can't get anywhere.

00:27:57.740 --> 00:28:00.057
If you come to our
Vietnamese class,

00:28:00.057 --> 00:28:01.640
you won't be making
anything you could

00:28:01.640 --> 00:28:03.380
get at a Vietnamese restaurant.

00:28:03.380 --> 00:28:05.210
You'll be getting
things that are served

00:28:05.210 --> 00:28:07.340
on the street in Vietnam.

00:28:07.340 --> 00:28:09.180
Our Vietnamese teacher
is from the island

00:28:09.180 --> 00:28:10.450
that fish sauce comes from.

00:28:10.450 --> 00:28:12.520
So he's a big fish sauce
guy and will teach you

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:14.520
all these different things
to do with fish sauce

00:28:14.520 --> 00:28:16.144
and how it's made
and all these things.

00:28:16.144 --> 00:28:17.960
So our teachers
are really, really

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:21.790
invested in a deep way
in getting people excited

00:28:21.790 --> 00:28:24.840
about, not only the food,
but the culture behind it

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:28.130
and the incredible richness
in every single country

00:28:28.130 --> 00:28:30.306
and every single region
and every country.

00:28:30.306 --> 00:28:32.415
Our Italian teacher does
12 classes in a year

00:28:32.415 --> 00:28:33.790
from 12 different
parts of Italy,

00:28:33.790 --> 00:28:35.331
and they're all
completely different.

00:28:35.331 --> 00:28:37.180
There's this amazing
diversity that's

00:28:37.180 --> 00:28:40.481
still out there in the
world, even though we're all

00:28:40.481 --> 00:28:42.730
eating hamburgers and fries
here in America every day.

00:28:42.730 --> 00:28:45.690
There are these
wonderful riches of food

00:28:45.690 --> 00:28:48.550
in culture and ingredients
that's out there.

00:28:48.550 --> 00:28:51.170
Our chef actually has
a book coming out today

00:28:51.170 --> 00:28:52.440
called "Dandelion and Quince."

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:54.880
It's about 36 unusual
fruits, vegetables,

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:57.892
and herbs that you may not have
heard of and may not be using.

00:28:57.892 --> 00:29:00.350
And it's all wonderful that
we're eating a lot of kale now,

00:29:00.350 --> 00:29:02.190
but there's a lot
more than kale that's

00:29:02.190 --> 00:29:04.600
out there in the
vegetable world, right?

00:29:04.600 --> 00:29:06.870
Let's eat celeriac.

00:29:06.870 --> 00:29:08.380
Let's eat stinging nettles.

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:10.100
Let's eat all these
other weird things

00:29:10.100 --> 00:29:13.234
that are amazing and delicious
and really good for you

00:29:13.234 --> 00:29:14.900
and have these different
health benefits

00:29:14.900 --> 00:29:18.574
and uses and cultural references
from around the world.

00:29:18.574 --> 00:29:20.240
So it's something
that we do that's kind

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:22.860
of beyond-- the skills is
like really giving people

00:29:22.860 --> 00:29:25.270
that cultural experience
and putting them

00:29:25.270 --> 00:29:27.510
in touch with other
home cooks like them

00:29:27.510 --> 00:29:29.380
from around the world.

00:29:29.380 --> 00:29:31.410
AUDIENCE: I was curious
to hear about how

00:29:31.410 --> 00:29:35.486
Bi-Rite has potentially evolved
as San Francisco has evolved.

00:29:35.486 --> 00:29:37.110
You were referencing
earlier that there

00:29:37.110 --> 00:29:40.900
are so many of these newfangled
things-- Uber, TaskRabbit--

00:29:40.900 --> 00:29:42.900
and we're like in this
hotbed of the city that's

00:29:42.900 --> 00:29:44.119
really on the edge.

00:29:44.119 --> 00:29:45.660
And I was curious
for a business that

00:29:45.660 --> 00:29:47.470
has existed for so
long, what is that

00:29:47.470 --> 00:29:50.680
like responding to a place
that's changing so rapidly?

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:53.110
SAM MOGANNAM: Yeah,
it's interesting.

00:29:53.110 --> 00:29:56.520
I feel like the change that's
happened in the last two years

00:29:56.520 --> 00:30:00.690
has been exponentially
faster than the change

00:30:00.690 --> 00:30:04.750
that we've experienced the last
16 years under my ownership.

00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:07.630
And we're still trying
to understand it.

00:30:07.630 --> 00:30:09.700
When we were talking
about this over lunch,

00:30:09.700 --> 00:30:15.220
part of the change that's
really significant to us

00:30:15.220 --> 00:30:20.790
is that there's been a shift
in who lives in San Francisco.

00:30:20.790 --> 00:30:24.160
And we spent years cultivating
these relationships.

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:25.680
It's what we do.

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:28.505
We sell food, but really
it's relationship building

00:30:28.505 --> 00:30:30.630
that we do, whether it's
with the people that we're

00:30:30.630 --> 00:30:33.360
selling the food to or the
people we're buying it from

00:30:33.360 --> 00:30:35.870
or the staff that we employ.

00:30:35.870 --> 00:30:41.040
And because of the economic
challenges that many people

00:30:41.040 --> 00:30:43.520
have faced, they've
either been displaced

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:45.400
and have had to
leave the Bay Area,

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:49.740
oftentimes leave the
state, or they cashed out

00:30:49.740 --> 00:30:54.320
because it was just too
lucrative that they were like,

00:30:54.320 --> 00:30:56.600
I can do better somewhere else.

00:30:56.600 --> 00:30:58.550
And so now we're
trying to get to know

00:30:58.550 --> 00:31:02.650
a whole new
demographic, and I feel

00:31:02.650 --> 00:31:04.960
like we're back in
startup mode again,

00:31:04.960 --> 00:31:10.170
yet in a slightly different way
where, when we started in '98

00:31:10.170 --> 00:31:16.861
and going through the crash
that happened-- the dot com

00:31:16.861 --> 00:31:19.360
bust that happened-- and then
the second crash that happened

00:31:19.360 --> 00:31:25.390
in 2009, we had just a
deep-rooted community of people

00:31:25.390 --> 00:31:26.470
that were loyal.

00:31:26.470 --> 00:31:28.670
Now we're finding that
we're having to actually

00:31:28.670 --> 00:31:32.830
start all over again with
a bunch of other markets

00:31:32.830 --> 00:31:35.850
and services that
are out there that

00:31:35.850 --> 00:31:40.720
are taking kind of like what
we've done and iterating on it

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:46.589
and offering local, organic,
sustainable everything.

00:31:46.589 --> 00:31:49.130
AUDIENCE: Sam, could you talk
a little bit about the decision

00:31:49.130 --> 00:31:51.560
and discussion around
opening the second location

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:55.610
on Divisadero and whether you
are planning further growth.

00:31:55.610 --> 00:31:57.332
At what point does
that make sense?

00:31:57.332 --> 00:31:58.790
SAM MOGANNAM: Yeah,
great question.

00:31:58.790 --> 00:32:02.870
The second market,
to be honest, was

00:32:02.870 --> 00:32:06.550
driven by a need
within the organization

00:32:06.550 --> 00:32:08.770
to create space
for people to grow.

00:32:08.770 --> 00:32:13.250
We were about 12-- let me think.

00:32:13.250 --> 00:32:16.730
It was like 13 years
in when we actually

00:32:16.730 --> 00:32:21.540
embarked on the search for
a new spot to do a market.

00:32:21.540 --> 00:32:24.849
And at the time, we had
several staff members

00:32:24.849 --> 00:32:26.390
who had been with
us for a long time.

00:32:29.230 --> 00:32:31.300
They wanted to grow,
like all of us.

00:32:31.300 --> 00:32:33.950
And we need to
constantly be challenged

00:32:33.950 --> 00:32:37.390
and to feel like that we're
taking the experiences

00:32:37.390 --> 00:32:40.190
that we're building
and building on them

00:32:40.190 --> 00:32:41.810
and doing more
and better things.

00:32:41.810 --> 00:32:45.270
And there were definitely
a few key people

00:32:45.270 --> 00:32:48.270
that if we didn't open
the second market,

00:32:48.270 --> 00:32:50.939
we probably would have lost.

00:32:50.939 --> 00:32:52.480
And so we started
the process, and we

00:32:52.480 --> 00:32:54.570
knew that we wanted to
be in a neighborhood

00:32:54.570 --> 00:32:57.640
where like-minded people
were going to be there.

00:32:57.640 --> 00:33:03.840
And Nopa, the restaurant, is
owned by two dear friends.

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:07.384
Lawrence, who's the chef,
and I have known each other

00:33:07.384 --> 00:33:09.050
since the days when
I had my restaurant,

00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:11.330
so back in 1993 we met.

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:13.632
And then Jeff Hanak,
who's his partner,

00:33:13.632 --> 00:33:15.090
and I went to high
school together.

00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:17.047
So I've known him
since I was 14,

00:33:17.047 --> 00:33:18.630
and we're both native
San Franciscans.

00:33:18.630 --> 00:33:23.000
And so that was a logical
spot for us to move into.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.180
And that building had heritage.

00:33:25.180 --> 00:33:30.320
It was an original Safeway back
in the late '20s, back when

00:33:30.320 --> 00:33:32.360
supermarkets didn't
have to be 50,000

00:33:32.360 --> 00:33:35.020
square feet with
four-acre parking lots

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:36.600
and take up all this space.

00:33:36.600 --> 00:33:40.560
Every neighborhood
had it's Bi-Rite

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:42.080
or it's mini little Safeway.

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:43.640
And people would walk.

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:49.780
They would use their bodies,
and they would shop and see

00:33:49.780 --> 00:33:54.310
each other in the grocery store,
get to know their butcher, Sam,

00:33:54.310 --> 00:33:58.560
and then walk and carry
their own groceries home

00:33:58.560 --> 00:34:00.170
and then cook.

00:34:00.170 --> 00:34:03.440
And so it was a
neighborhood that

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:08.400
also had been asking for us.

00:34:08.400 --> 00:34:11.469
There were several neighborhoods
that wanted us to move,

00:34:11.469 --> 00:34:13.070
and that was one.

00:34:13.070 --> 00:34:17.360
And then with regards to
future growth, while we're

00:34:17.360 --> 00:34:25.315
in the process of building out
the Divisadero store, about 8,

00:34:25.315 --> 00:34:28.020
10 months in,
conversations internally

00:34:28.020 --> 00:34:31.139
started to happen around who
we're going to move over there,

00:34:31.139 --> 00:34:35.120
trying to start to build
the outline of a team--

00:34:35.120 --> 00:34:36.429
the leadership team.

00:34:36.429 --> 00:34:38.658
And I had several
staff members asking me

00:34:38.658 --> 00:34:40.949
about whether there was an
opportunity for them to move

00:34:40.949 --> 00:34:43.929
over there and even more
staff members asking me

00:34:43.929 --> 00:34:45.850
what the future of
Bi-Rite looked like.

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:46.710
They wanted to know
if we were going

00:34:46.710 --> 00:34:48.168
to be the next
Whole Foods or if we

00:34:48.168 --> 00:34:51.110
were going to continue to
expand in San Francisco

00:34:51.110 --> 00:34:54.460
or if we were looking
out of the Bay Area.

00:34:54.460 --> 00:34:59.780
And I didn't have an answer
that was totally codified

00:34:59.780 --> 00:35:03.240
and that wasn't one
that all of us shared.

00:35:03.240 --> 00:35:06.380
And so we embarked
on the process

00:35:06.380 --> 00:35:08.180
of writing a 10-year vision.

00:35:08.180 --> 00:35:11.020
And it took us a
year and a half.

00:35:11.020 --> 00:35:14.690
It usually takes a
long time to write

00:35:14.690 --> 00:35:16.710
our missions and our
visions, because we really

00:35:16.710 --> 00:35:19.640
want to have space in
between particular sessions

00:35:19.640 --> 00:35:22.430
so there's opportunity
for reflection,

00:35:22.430 --> 00:35:24.840
and we also are very
Socratic and try

00:35:24.840 --> 00:35:27.115
to involve as many people
as we possibly can.

00:35:27.115 --> 00:35:28.740
And the vision writing
process actually

00:35:28.740 --> 00:35:32.500
involved all 250 people who were
working in the organization.

00:35:32.500 --> 00:35:35.020
And at each point when
we had the drafts,

00:35:35.020 --> 00:35:37.620
we were delivering the drafts
in both English and in Spanish

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:40.280
to make sure that all the
populations in our company

00:35:40.280 --> 00:35:46.100
really had an opportunity to
contribute to what they felt

00:35:46.100 --> 00:35:48.120
was good or not good,
what they wanted to see,

00:35:48.120 --> 00:35:49.870
what they didn't want to see.

00:35:49.870 --> 00:35:53.680
And so we got a bunch
of rich feedback,

00:35:53.680 --> 00:35:55.740
kept modifying the
drafts, and then

00:35:55.740 --> 00:35:59.790
rolled out with our final
vision at the end of 2013.

00:35:59.790 --> 00:36:03.240
And so it's a 2024
vision, and in it our goal

00:36:03.240 --> 00:36:06.820
is to have one to three
new businesses by 2024.

00:36:06.820 --> 00:36:10.950
So continued slow,
deliberate growth

00:36:10.950 --> 00:36:14.670
but businesses that are
synergistic with each other.

00:36:14.670 --> 00:36:16.480
We're also a unique model.

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:18.990
All the businesses share
a lot of resources.

00:36:18.990 --> 00:36:20.840
There's a lot of
interbusiness between them,

00:36:20.840 --> 00:36:24.410
like our creamery sells
baked goods and ice

00:36:24.410 --> 00:36:27.550
cream to the two markets
and to our catering company.

00:36:27.550 --> 00:36:30.390
And so we wanted to make sure
that the businesses continue

00:36:30.390 --> 00:36:36.230
to have that interconnectivity
that makes us, I think,

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:41.100
so dynamic and creates a
much stronger foundation

00:36:41.100 --> 00:36:44.900
but also wanted to stay
here in San Francisco,

00:36:44.900 --> 00:36:47.250
in communities where
we feel we can go deep.

00:36:47.250 --> 00:36:52.160
For us, it's really not about
the volume of what we do.

00:36:52.160 --> 00:36:54.350
It's about the
impact that we have

00:36:54.350 --> 00:36:57.810
and continuing to get
closer to achieving

00:36:57.810 --> 00:36:59.660
our mission of
creating community

00:36:59.660 --> 00:37:01.840
and seeing social change happen.

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:04.440
So that's the plan.

00:37:04.440 --> 00:37:11.480
We're starting rumblings of what
maybe the third store might be.

00:37:11.480 --> 00:37:17.020
So I think next year, 2017,
determining that next step will

00:37:17.020 --> 00:37:19.682
be part of our strategic plan.

00:37:19.682 --> 00:37:21.140
JESS: So to the
point of community,

00:37:21.140 --> 00:37:23.556
Sarah, I know we've talked a
lot about the cooking classes

00:37:23.556 --> 00:37:25.530
at 18 Reasons, but
I'd also love for you

00:37:25.530 --> 00:37:28.480
to talk a little bit about
the Feed Your People events

00:37:28.480 --> 00:37:32.357
and community dinners,
because I, at least, found

00:37:32.357 --> 00:37:34.190
that to be a really
interesting thing that I

00:37:34.190 --> 00:37:35.730
didn't know about 18 Reasons.

00:37:35.730 --> 00:37:36.760
SARAH NELSON: Yeah.

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:40.450
Another unique thing that we do
that a lot of cooking schools

00:37:40.450 --> 00:37:44.030
don't do is we open our
doors for dinners a couple

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:45.100
times a month.

00:37:45.100 --> 00:37:46.860
So on the last
Wednesday of the month,

00:37:46.860 --> 00:37:49.670
we do a $10 dinner--
a community dinner.

00:37:49.670 --> 00:37:52.610
We do two seatings of 40
people, and 18 Reasons

00:37:52.610 --> 00:37:54.480
is about half the
size of this room.

00:37:54.480 --> 00:37:57.470
So you can imagine 40 people
coming on in, squeezing

00:37:57.470 --> 00:38:02.360
together, eating one plate of
food that could be anything.

00:38:02.360 --> 00:38:04.297
This month, two
of our volunteers

00:38:04.297 --> 00:38:05.630
are actually cooking the dinner.

00:38:05.630 --> 00:38:08.290
They're a brother and sister
who grew up in Martinique,

00:38:08.290 --> 00:38:10.830
and they're doing a kind of
French-Caribbean community

00:38:10.830 --> 00:38:12.190
dinner.

00:38:12.190 --> 00:38:13.720
Last month, we had a fish fry.

00:38:13.720 --> 00:38:16.060
Our Jam and Preserving
teacher who grew up in Harlem

00:38:16.060 --> 00:38:19.370
having fried fish every Friday
night, wanted to do a fish fry.

00:38:19.370 --> 00:38:24.170
So we made fried fish
sandwiches with a heroic butcher

00:38:24.170 --> 00:38:27.700
from Bi-Rite helping us out with
the fish and frying fish for 40

00:38:27.700 --> 00:38:30.460
people in a pan about this big.

00:38:30.460 --> 00:38:33.260
And next month
actually Bi-Rite is

00:38:33.260 --> 00:38:37.290
going to work with us to do some
of their dinner deli specials

00:38:37.290 --> 00:38:39.000
for the community dinner.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.400
In October, we usually
do an Oktoberfest sausage

00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:44.340
and sauerkraut business
where I make sauerkraut.

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:46.470
I love fermenting
and preserving.

00:38:46.470 --> 00:38:48.607
And our chef cooks the sausages.

00:38:48.607 --> 00:38:51.065
And it's really just whatever
pops into our mind that month

00:38:51.065 --> 00:38:52.606
that seems like it
would be fun to do

00:38:52.606 --> 00:38:53.812
and that people would enjoy.

00:38:53.812 --> 00:38:56.020
It's totally different, and
we do two seatings of 40,

00:38:56.020 --> 00:38:57.560
so we have 80 people
coming through.

00:38:57.560 --> 00:38:58.820
We have a lot of regulars.

00:38:58.820 --> 00:39:01.040
The first seating, a lot
of people bring their kids.

00:39:01.040 --> 00:39:03.540
The second seating, a lot of
people bring bottles of wine.

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:05.970
And people just hang out
and meet their neighbors,

00:39:05.970 --> 00:39:06.990
have a great time.

00:39:06.990 --> 00:39:08.690
And through our
community dinners,

00:39:08.690 --> 00:39:11.490
we met a cookbook author
named Leslie Jonath, who

00:39:11.490 --> 00:39:14.670
wanted to put together a
book of big-batch recipes.

00:39:14.670 --> 00:39:18.180
So how to cook for a
crowd or with the crowd,

00:39:18.180 --> 00:39:20.250
and this book is called
"Feed Your People."

00:39:20.250 --> 00:39:22.500
It's coming out
next year, and it's

00:39:22.500 --> 00:39:25.190
a collaboration between
18 Reasons and Leslie

00:39:25.190 --> 00:39:27.480
and a bunch of chefs from
all over the country.

00:39:27.480 --> 00:39:31.250
So she asked restaurant chefs
and home cooks and people

00:39:31.250 --> 00:39:33.530
she found out about who were
famous in their community

00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:36.072
for having big gatherings and
got recipes, not something they

00:39:36.072 --> 00:39:38.154
would make in their
restaurant, but what would you

00:39:38.154 --> 00:39:40.560
cook if you had 20 people
coming over to your house?

00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:43.160
And so it's got everything
from like seafood boils

00:39:43.160 --> 00:39:46.664
to tamale making
parties to slab pie.

00:39:46.664 --> 00:39:48.830
This is my favorite recipe
that I learned this year.

00:39:48.830 --> 00:39:53.480
Take a giant cookie sheet,
dough, fruit, dough,

00:39:53.480 --> 00:39:55.490
bake it like a giant Pop-tart.

00:39:55.490 --> 00:39:57.230
It's so good.

00:39:57.230 --> 00:39:58.470
Oh, my god.

00:39:58.470 --> 00:39:59.980
So that's going in the book.

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:02.080
And we started
doing some dinners

00:40:02.080 --> 00:40:04.330
with some chefs who had been
contributing to the book.

00:40:04.330 --> 00:40:07.364
So our next door
neighbor is Namu Gaji.

00:40:07.364 --> 00:40:08.280
Has anyone been there?

00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:10.140
The Korean-Japanese
place on the corner?

00:40:10.140 --> 00:40:13.750
So we did a Bo Ssam, a
big traditional dinner

00:40:13.750 --> 00:40:17.530
with pork belly and oysters
and all these things with them.

00:40:17.530 --> 00:40:22.870
Pableaux Johnson, who's an
advocate for New Orleans food

00:40:22.870 --> 00:40:25.050
culture, is coming with
his rice and beans road

00:40:25.050 --> 00:40:26.720
show next Monday.

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:29.649
Rice and beans traditionally
eaten on Mondays in New Orleans

00:40:29.649 --> 00:40:31.190
while people are
doing their laundry,

00:40:31.190 --> 00:40:33.760
cooking something
easy, and he's coming.

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:35.640
We're going to do 40
people, rice and beans.

00:40:35.640 --> 00:40:38.030
It's kind of a Feed
Your People event.

00:40:38.030 --> 00:40:41.720
So we're always trying to
bring people in to 18 Reasons.

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:44.897
We want people to cook, but it's
kind of a little secret part

00:40:44.897 --> 00:40:45.480
of 18 Reasons.

00:40:45.480 --> 00:40:47.771
If you don't like to cook,
there's still stuff for you.

00:40:47.771 --> 00:40:49.980
You can come and
experience home cooking

00:40:49.980 --> 00:40:51.820
that other people
have cooked for you.

00:40:51.820 --> 00:40:54.290
So our Feed Your People dinners
and our monthly community

00:40:54.290 --> 00:40:56.840
dinner are a great way
to come and check us out.

00:40:56.840 --> 00:40:57.990
SAM MOGANNAM: And to
meet your neighbors.

00:40:57.990 --> 00:40:58.300
SARAH NELSON: Yeah.

00:40:58.300 --> 00:40:59.340
SAM MOGANNAM: That's one of the
things that I love about it.

00:40:59.340 --> 00:41:00.390
SARAH NELSON: It's
eight people at a table.

00:41:00.390 --> 00:41:02.139
So you're definitely
going to meet people.

00:41:02.139 --> 00:41:03.410
SAM MOGANNAM: That's cool.

00:41:03.410 --> 00:41:05.440
AUDIENCE: So Sam, you
mentioned that after kind

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:06.890
of evaluating your
long-term plan,

00:41:06.890 --> 00:41:09.780
you had the interest to focus
your efforts in the Bay Area.

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:12.750
But a lot of the issues that
you guys described about people

00:41:12.750 --> 00:41:14.360
not knowing how
to eat sustainably

00:41:14.360 --> 00:41:17.560
or not knowing how to cook is
a pretty big issue nationally,

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:18.450
internationally.

00:41:18.450 --> 00:41:19.960
And I think that
what you've done

00:41:19.960 --> 00:41:22.390
is actually a great
model for expanding

00:41:22.390 --> 00:41:24.580
this type of
education and covering

00:41:24.580 --> 00:41:26.720
these issues elsewhere.

00:41:26.720 --> 00:41:29.580
So aside from not having
a physical presence there,

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:31.192
is there any kind
of alternative thing

00:41:31.192 --> 00:41:33.650
that you guys have been thinking
about where you can expand

00:41:33.650 --> 00:41:36.750
your influence in other parts
of the US, to maybe bring

00:41:36.750 --> 00:41:39.500
your lessons and your
expertise to solve

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:40.630
these problems elsewhere?

00:41:40.630 --> 00:41:41.421
SAM MOGANNAM: Yeah.

00:41:41.421 --> 00:41:43.790
I think we've done
a lot in that arena.

00:41:46.920 --> 00:41:50.770
I saw several people buying
the book, "Eat Good Food."

00:41:50.770 --> 00:41:54.770
That was written with
specifically that intent,

00:41:54.770 --> 00:41:58.240
to be that empowering-- that
teaching tool-- to give people

00:41:58.240 --> 00:42:02.247
the basics that they needed to
know while they were shopping

00:42:02.247 --> 00:42:04.830
in the grocery store or wherever
they were getting their food.

00:42:04.830 --> 00:42:09.550
And really, for me, it distills
down to the five key questions

00:42:09.550 --> 00:42:12.760
that I think anybody
who's going to eat

00:42:12.760 --> 00:42:15.609
and who's in a position of
buying food should be asking.

00:42:15.609 --> 00:42:16.900
Where is that food coming from?

00:42:16.900 --> 00:42:17.640
How is it grown?

00:42:17.640 --> 00:42:18.740
Who grew it?

00:42:18.740 --> 00:42:19.270
Right?

00:42:19.270 --> 00:42:21.820
Where it was grown
and how it tastes.

00:42:21.820 --> 00:42:23.420
And it's really
incredible, if you

00:42:23.420 --> 00:42:26.220
walk into any
traditional supermarket

00:42:26.220 --> 00:42:29.100
and ask one of those
questions to whoever

00:42:29.100 --> 00:42:30.740
is working in the
produce department,

00:42:30.740 --> 00:42:32.370
they won't know the answer.

00:42:32.370 --> 00:42:35.970
The answer that really depresses
me that they can't answer

00:42:35.970 --> 00:42:37.010
is how it tastes.

00:42:37.010 --> 00:42:38.690
The people working
in those stores

00:42:38.690 --> 00:42:40.740
themselves couldn't tell
you which of the apples

00:42:40.740 --> 00:42:42.510
was the best tasting apples,
because they haven't really

00:42:42.510 --> 00:42:43.160
taken the time.

00:42:43.160 --> 00:42:47.080
And it's not really of value
to them in that company.

00:42:47.080 --> 00:42:51.860
So I think the book has
sold over 30,000 copies

00:42:51.860 --> 00:42:55.210
and some schools have bought it.

00:42:55.210 --> 00:42:58.490
That's one thing that I
think has been a huge help.

00:42:58.490 --> 00:43:02.310
And I know several grocery
stores use it as well

00:43:02.310 --> 00:43:05.050
to train and teach their staff.

00:43:05.050 --> 00:43:08.930
I speak and I talk at
conferences fairly regularly,

00:43:08.930 --> 00:43:10.430
trying to influence
other retailers.

00:43:10.430 --> 00:43:13.910
I belong to a few
retailer organizations,

00:43:13.910 --> 00:43:16.160
and we're really transparent
and open about everything

00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:16.960
that we do.

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:20.490
We share our business practices,
we share our staff manual,

00:43:20.490 --> 00:43:22.480
we share our training
material, because I want

00:43:22.480 --> 00:43:25.560
other independents to succeed.

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:30.570
It's really important for me
to see community-based markets

00:43:30.570 --> 00:43:33.730
and community-based
organizations of all kinds

00:43:33.730 --> 00:43:36.890
really thrive,
because they become

00:43:36.890 --> 00:43:41.800
really amazing identifiers for
the people that live there.

00:43:41.800 --> 00:43:45.900
Bi-Rite's a really great example
of kind of a transformation

00:43:45.900 --> 00:43:47.240
of a community.

00:43:47.240 --> 00:43:51.260
Even though the market was
in my family since 1964,

00:43:51.260 --> 00:43:55.120
it went out of our
family from 1989 to 1997.

00:43:55.120 --> 00:43:57.995
And the neighborhood really went
through a pretty crappy period

00:43:57.995 --> 00:43:58.495
of time.

00:43:58.495 --> 00:44:01.380
Dolores Park was taken
over by a couple of gangs,

00:44:01.380 --> 00:44:05.430
and my dad would never let me
go play there when I was a kid,

00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:08.740
because it was pretty rough.

00:44:08.740 --> 00:44:13.550
By the time that we got the
store back in 1997, because it

00:44:13.550 --> 00:44:15.510
was out of our family,
there were metal grates

00:44:15.510 --> 00:44:17.864
on the windows, and all the
storefronts on 18th Street

00:44:17.864 --> 00:44:19.280
had metal grates
on their windows,

00:44:19.280 --> 00:44:21.772
because break-ins
were pretty normal.

00:44:21.772 --> 00:44:23.230
And there were less
than-- with all

00:44:23.230 --> 00:44:25.605
those commercial storefronts,
there was probably like 25,

00:44:25.605 --> 00:44:31.820
30 people employed on that
block, and after we opened,

00:44:31.820 --> 00:44:34.010
Delfina opened a
few months later,

00:44:34.010 --> 00:44:37.817
Tartine opened, Namu
Gaji, Izakaya's, Yuzuki.

00:44:37.817 --> 00:44:39.650
There's a lot of new
businesses, and there's

00:44:39.650 --> 00:44:42.300
like over 400 people now
working on that block, one

00:44:42.300 --> 00:44:43.040
single block.

00:44:45.600 --> 00:44:49.080
And that block has kind
of become a real example

00:44:49.080 --> 00:44:53.885
of a community hub in a lot
of ways around the country,

00:44:53.885 --> 00:44:58.390
and it's really identified
by a lot of developers

00:44:58.390 --> 00:45:02.710
as like a model for
what they envision

00:45:02.710 --> 00:45:05.560
in transforming communities.

00:45:05.560 --> 00:45:10.140
And so we've been
this influence,

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:14.870
I guess, and this inspiration
for community development

00:45:14.870 --> 00:45:18.250
but also for just other
retailers and other businesses

00:45:18.250 --> 00:45:22.930
that are just not looking at
business as a means of bringing

00:45:22.930 --> 00:45:29.610
a bottom line, but as a means
of building relationships

00:45:29.610 --> 00:45:33.090
and creating a stronger fabric
in the community, a tighter

00:45:33.090 --> 00:45:33.878
fabric.

00:45:33.878 --> 00:45:36.252
SARAH NELSON: You also invented
salted caramel ice cream.

00:45:36.252 --> 00:45:38.460
SAM MOGANNAM: Yeah, we did.

00:45:38.460 --> 00:45:40.699
SARAH NELSON: Huge influence.

00:45:40.699 --> 00:45:42.490
SAM MOGANNAM: We were
actually just talking

00:45:42.490 --> 00:45:44.150
about this yesterday.

00:45:44.150 --> 00:45:48.730
And sometimes our generosity
and sharing has bitten us.

00:45:48.730 --> 00:45:51.100
There was a woman who was
planning on opening up

00:45:51.100 --> 00:45:53.700
an ice cream shop in
Seattle who wanted to spend

00:45:53.700 --> 00:45:55.270
a couple of days with us.

00:45:55.270 --> 00:45:57.740
And we let her,
because when went

00:45:57.740 --> 00:46:03.930
to open up the creamery,
nobody that owned an ice cream

00:46:03.930 --> 00:46:06.200
store would actually let
us spend any time with them

00:46:06.200 --> 00:46:08.620
to learn how to use
the Emery Thompson,

00:46:08.620 --> 00:46:11.520
this machine-- this batch
freezer that makes ice cream.

00:46:11.520 --> 00:46:14.480
And my wife Anne, who
developed the recipes

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:17.229
and is our head pastry
chef, during her time

00:46:17.229 --> 00:46:18.770
as a pastry chef in
restaurants, we'd

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:20.740
use one of those
old-school White Mountains,

00:46:20.740 --> 00:46:23.370
you know, like the wooden
bucket with the ice and the salt

00:46:23.370 --> 00:46:25.941
and it would crank
and go eehhh, and then

00:46:25.941 --> 00:46:27.440
you'd know that ice
cream was almost

00:46:27.440 --> 00:46:29.523
done when the motor was
struggling because the ice

00:46:29.523 --> 00:46:30.350
cream was thick.

00:46:30.350 --> 00:46:32.891
And so we had no idea how to
use these larger batch freezers.

00:46:32.891 --> 00:46:36.310
And so we made a commitment
saying, you know what?

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:39.710
Everyone shut us out, but we're
not going to shut people out.

00:46:39.710 --> 00:46:43.530
And so she came and spent
a couple days with us

00:46:43.530 --> 00:46:44.880
and opened up her shop.

00:46:44.880 --> 00:46:48.070
And she had salted
caramel, honey lavender,

00:46:48.070 --> 00:46:52.380
balsamic strawberry,
roasted banana.

00:46:52.380 --> 00:46:57.480
But the kicker was she had Sam's
Sunday on the menu as well.

00:46:57.480 --> 00:47:00.450
JESS: So I just want to ask one
last question as we wrap up,

00:47:00.450 --> 00:47:03.690
and I also want to thank,
first of all, Paige,

00:47:03.690 --> 00:47:05.190
who is hiding in the audience.

00:47:05.190 --> 00:47:06.990
Paige is our farmers'
market specialist,

00:47:06.990 --> 00:47:10.180
and she arranged all
this, and she is awesome

00:47:10.180 --> 00:47:11.736
if you get a chance
to talk to her.

00:47:14.270 --> 00:47:17.000
As you mentioned, this is
a room full of the choir,

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:18.880
and so I just want
to ask you, what

00:47:18.880 --> 00:47:21.130
can the people here
who are already

00:47:21.130 --> 00:47:24.660
engaged home cooks do to
help the people around them

00:47:24.660 --> 00:47:28.321
become more engaged in
community of food and home

00:47:28.321 --> 00:47:30.820
cooking and self-empowerment
and all of the wonderful things

00:47:30.820 --> 00:47:33.590
that you guys
talked about today?

00:47:33.590 --> 00:47:35.870
SARAH NELSON: Invite your
friends over for dinner.

