I used to live in
Paris, and in Paris

00:47:59.231 --> 00:48:00.730
you go out to dinner
at 8:00 and you

00:48:00.730 --> 00:48:01.770
leave the restaurant
at midnight,

00:48:01.770 --> 00:48:02.990
and that was your
plan for the night.

00:48:02.990 --> 00:48:03.491
That's it.

00:48:03.491 --> 00:48:04.906
Here, you go to a
restaurant 8:00,

00:48:04.906 --> 00:48:06.370
you're back on the
street at 9:00,

00:48:06.370 --> 00:48:08.300
which means you have to go
spend more money at a bar

00:48:08.300 --> 00:48:09.220
or something if you want
to keep hanging out, right?

00:48:09.220 --> 00:48:11.280
When I moved back here,
I couldn't believe it.

00:48:11.280 --> 00:48:11.990
I'm like, what are we doing?

00:48:11.990 --> 00:48:12.781
What do we do next?

00:48:12.781 --> 00:48:13.646
It's only 9:00.

00:48:13.646 --> 00:48:15.520
But if you're at home,
there's no time limit.

00:48:15.520 --> 00:48:16.660
No one's going to
turn your table.

00:48:16.660 --> 00:48:18.025
You can hang out as
long as you want,

00:48:18.025 --> 00:48:19.860
and you actually linger
and enjoy your meal

00:48:19.860 --> 00:48:21.790
and hang out with your friends
as long as you want to.

00:48:21.790 --> 00:48:22.970
SAM MOGANNAM: And drink as
much wine as you want to.

00:48:22.970 --> 00:48:24.969
SARAH NELSON: Drink as
much wine as you want to,

00:48:24.969 --> 00:48:26.070
and it's half the price.

00:48:26.070 --> 00:48:27.236
SAM MOGANNAM: Yeah, I agree.

00:48:27.236 --> 00:48:31.156
I think cooking more is a great
way to inspire others to cook,

00:48:31.156 --> 00:48:33.030
and feeding people is
such a wonderful thing.

00:48:33.030 --> 00:48:36.280
I also think coming
to 18 Reasons,

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:39.490
we rely on a network
of 900 volunteers

00:48:39.490 --> 00:48:41.340
to do the work that we do.

00:48:41.340 --> 00:48:43.050
The cooking, the
free programming,

00:48:43.050 --> 00:48:46.940
we're teaching 2,500
students a year,

00:48:46.940 --> 00:48:50.190
and we only have a paid staff
of 10, and several of those

00:48:50.190 --> 00:48:53.010
are AmeriCorps volunteers.

00:48:53.010 --> 00:48:55.780
It takes a village to
make this work happen,

00:48:55.780 --> 00:48:58.980
and it's happening in the
five Bay Area counties.

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:05.360
And so we always need support,
both in time and financial.

00:49:05.360 --> 00:49:07.530
It would be a huge
thing to help with.

00:49:07.530 --> 00:49:11.670
And attending classes at
18 Reasons as well, I feel,

00:49:11.670 --> 00:49:15.412
is so important
because you're actually

00:49:15.412 --> 00:49:17.620
getting to know the people
that live in the community

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:20.430
that you live and work in.

00:49:20.430 --> 00:49:23.690
And that, to me, is what
makes our society stronger.

00:49:23.690 --> 00:49:25.380
The more people
that we get to know,

00:49:25.380 --> 00:49:29.010
the more diverse the
population of people

00:49:29.010 --> 00:49:31.937
that we interact with,
the more empathetic

00:49:31.937 --> 00:49:33.520
and I think the more
empowered that we

00:49:33.520 --> 00:49:39.610
are with our view of what
a strong, tight, successful

00:49:39.610 --> 00:49:41.200
community looks like.

00:49:41.200 --> 00:49:43.460
JESS: Thank you guys
so much for being here.

00:49:43.460 --> 00:49:44.910
It's awesome, and
it was an honor.

00:49:44.910 --> 00:49:45.430
SAM MOGANNAM: Thanks.

00:49:45.430 --> 00:49:47.330
JESS: And thank you all
for sticking around,

